  "text": "The security of RSA cryptosystem is based entirely on the structure of the multiplicative group Z/NZ, where N is the product of two large primes p and q, typically of equal bit length. Thus, N is selected in such a way such that the problem of factoring the modulus N is computationally hard. It can be proved that factoring N is polynomially (in time) equivalent to the problem of computing the secret key d if d < N and it is an open problem to prove or disprove the polynomial time equivalence of these problems to the problem of extracting e th -roots in the ring Z N [CITATION_1] . However, most of the attacks are based on misuse of the system, bad choice parameters or flaws in implementations [CITATION_2] ). The significance of cryptographic key size to the security of cryptosystem is emphasized by [CITATION_3] , where they offer guidelines for the determination of key sizes for symmetric cryptosystems, RSA and discrete logarithm based cryptosystems over finite fields and groups of elliptic curves over prime fields.",
